I was exploring this. I placed some logs to check the state of the element that is getting detached from the frame. Came across something confusing.

In `frame.ts`, 
```js
elementsToFilter.forEach((element) => {
    if (
      element.frameId &&
      !isFrameElement(element) &&
      !isElementInFrame(element, allElements, appState)
    ) {
      console.log("element: ", element);
      console.log("element.frameId: ", element.frameId);
      console.log("added an element to remove from it's frame!");
      elementsToRemove.add(element);
    }
  });   
```

The `frameId` when logging the complete object is NULL but when I log `element.frameId`, the correct `frameId` is logged on the console. 

<img width="647" alt="image" src="https://github.com/excalidraw/excalidraw/assets/72058551/3852c8cc-3e53-4050-9bcb-dbc09da1874e">

## The Problem
The align action causes any element that moves to be detached from the frame because a new element is created when there is a translation.


## Explanation
Function `newElementWith` in mutateElement.ts:
1. returns the same element it was passed if there were no changes to its data
2. returns a new element if there were changes(like a translation)
```typescript
  if (!didChange) {
    return element;
  }

  return {
    ...element,
    ...updates,
    updated: getUpdatedTimestamp(),
    version: element.version + 1,
    versionNonce: randomInteger(),
  };
```
Essentially, if an element needs to be moved, a new element will be created. As a result, the `getContainingFrame` function, which is called by `getTargetFrame`, will return null because it tries to get an element not currently in the scene(the element was just created).
`getContainingFrame`:

```typescript
if (element.frameId) {
    if (elementsMap) {
      return (elementsMap.get(element.frameId) ||
        null) as null | ExcalidrawFrameLikeElement;
    }
    //the new element passed into this function is not in the scene, returning null
    return (
      (Scene.getScene(element)?.getElement(
        element.frameId,
      ) as ExcalidrawFrameLikeElement) || null
    );
  }
  return null;
```

`getTargetFrame` in frame.ts will evaluate to null, which means we don't even get to check if the aligned element is still overlapping, it just gets queued up for removal.

```typescript
  //null frame
  const frame = getTargetFrame(element, appState); 
  const _element = isTextElement(element)
    ? getContainerElement(element) || element
    : element;
  if (frame) { //this block is skipped
    // Perf improvement:
    // For an element that's already in a frame, if it's not being dragged
    // then there is no need to refer to geometry (which, yes, is slow) to check if it's in a frame.
    // It has to be in its containing frame.
    if (
      !appState.selectedElementIds[element.id] ||
      !appState.selectedElementsAreBeingDragged
    ) {
      return true;
    }

    if (_element.groupIds.length === 0) {
      return elementOverlapsWithFrame(_element, frame);
    }
```

So any element that is translated during alignment will always return false for the function `isElementInFrame`, even if it is still in the frame position-wise.

```typescript
elementsToFilter.forEach((element) => {
    if (
      element.frameId &&
      !isFrameLikeElement(element) &&
      !isElementInFrame(element, allElements, appState, "inFrame") // false because no frame retrieved for element not in scene yet.
    ) {
      elementsToRemove.add(element);
    }
  });
```
 
 Mutating the translated element instead of creating a new one would solve this issue, so would attaching the new element to the scene. I'm not sure how this should be done or if there is a better way, would love to talk about it.

## Secondary Issue: measuring overlap

