| **Grouped**  | **Ungrouped**  |
|:-:|:-:|
| <img src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/fce52798-f249-43e5-a7c6-b2d238a05507" alt="Grouped items" width=350> | <img src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/99f00305-60fe-4e48-807f-742bfdf2fa09" alt="Ungrouped items" width=350>  |
|`[Array(2)]`   |  `[Array(1), Array(1)]` |

In `align.ts`

```ts
const selectionBoundingBox = getCommonBoundingBox(selectedElements);

  return groups.flatMap((group) => {
    const translation = calculateTranslation(
      group,
      selectionBoundingBox,
      alignment,
    );
    return group.map((element) =>
      newElementWith(element, {
        x: element.x + translation.x,
        y: element.y + translation.y,
      }),
    );
  });
```
Calling `calculateTranslation` on the the group results in `noTranslation` because `selectionBoundingBox` will be the same as `groupBoundingBox` computed in `calculateTranslation`.

One way to fix this is to detect when all of the selected elements are part of a group. If we change `getMaximumGroups` in `groups.ts` to check if all the elements are part of a single group and in this case return each element of the group as an `Array` of a single element by changing the function return from

```ts
return Array.from(groups.values());
```

to

```ts
const groupsArray = Array.from(groups.values());

  return groupsArray.length > 1
    ? groupsArray
    : groupsArray.flatMap((group) => group.map((elements) => [elements]));
```
Will result in `calculateTranslation` being called for each element of the group therefore making `selectionBoundingBox != groupBoundingBox` and applying the translation correctly.

