@VineshRajkumar There are a lot of PRs in the queue attempting to fix various (usually small) issues. The Excalidraw team doesn't always have the capacity to work with submitters if they haven't taken the right approach to the fix or feature from the get-go. Explaining why a direction is not the right one (1) takes a lot of time (2) even after explaining it leads to more questions regarding the why than there is capacity to answer. 

Christopher's PR was spot on and required very limited review time, so it got merged.

Excalidraw is admittendly very complex, its architecture and design decisions are often non-trivial, so it's a bit of a guess which direction is the right one if you're not spending significant time with the code base. In general small, performant changes with very limited side effects are favored.

@Mounir-abaddah   it's an implementation issue. The problem is that you're trying to control Excalidraw elements through React state instead of using the proper initialData prop

```
import { Excalidraw } from "@excalidraw/excalidraw";
import "@excalidraw/excalidraw/index.css";
import { useEffect, useState } from "react";
import type { ExcalidrawInitialDataState } from "@excalidraw/excalidraw/types";

export default function DrawExcalidraw() {
  const [initialData, setInitialData] = useState<ExcalidrawInitialDataState | null>(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    const savedDrawing = localStorage.getItem("excalidraw-drawing");
    if (savedDrawing) {
      try {
        const parsedData = JSON.parse(savedDrawing);
        setInitialData({
          elements: parsedData.elements || [],
          appState: parsedData.appState || {},
        });
      } catch (error) {
        console.error("Failed to parse saved drawing:", error);
      }
    }
  }, []);

  return (
    <div style={{ height: "500px" }}>
      <Excalidraw
        initialData={initialData}
        onChange={(elements, appState) => {
          const dataToSave = { elements, appState };
          localStorage.setItem("excalidraw-drawing", JSON.stringify(dataToSave));
        }}
      />
    </div>
  );
}

```

